# Project context and skills

This repository is the **Default Context Generator**. Use the context documentation and the skills below to keep things consistent.

## Where the context is

- **Overview and index:** [docs/context/README.md](../../docs/context/README.md)
- **By area:** [extension.md](../../docs/context/extension.md), [skills-e-rules.md](../../docs/context/skills-e-rules.md), [docs-tecnico.md](../../docs/context/docs-tecnico.md), [doc-existing-repos.md](../../docs/context/doc-existing-repos.md) (interpreting existing doc in target repos)

## Skill allocation (in this repo)

| When working on | Use as guide |
|-----------------|--------------|
| `src/extension.ts`, commands, clipboard, VS Code API | No specific domain skill; see [VS Code Extension API](https://code.visualstudio.com/api). TypeScript. |
| `.cursor/skills/`, `.cursor/rules/`, generator content | **docs-tecnico** (structure, Cursor format); **default-context-generator** for the workflow. |
| `README.md`, `PROJECT_IDEA.md` (if present), `docs/` | **docs-tecnico**; keep in sync with code and .cursor/. |
| Request to "generate context" or "get context" | Rule **gerar-contexto** + skill **default-context-generator** (see .cursor/rules/gerar-contexto.mdc). |

## Keep documentation up to date

When you change code, architecture, or conventions that affect what is described in `docs/context/` (or in README.md / `PROJECT_IDEA.md` when present), **update the corresponding document in the same workflow**. That avoids drift between code and context and keeps the context in sync with the current state.

